Note:
PowerShell Lex + Parse Smoke Probe (Stage A)

Bounded proof that the PowerShell front-of-pipeline (lexer + parser) is REAL
and TERMINATES on a broad slice of real PowerShell:

    PowerShell source
      -> tokenize        (powershell_lexer: param() blocks, typed params,
                          $variables + $script:/$env: scopes, Verb-Noun cmdlets
                          with -Named/positional/switch params, pipelines |,
                          if/elseif/else, foreach/for/while/do, switch,
                          try/catch/finally, hashtables @{}, arrays @(),
                          script blocks { }, "$($x)" interpolation,
                          -eq/-ne/-gt/-match/-like operators, # and <# #> comments)
      -> create_parser   (wire the token stream into the parser state)
      -> parse_script    (walk the token stream into the AST)

This probe deliberately does NOT assert content round-trip: the PowerShell
parser productions do not yet populate node value/name payloads and the
lexer does not retain per-token lexeme text, so HIR content survival is the
subject of a separate from-scratch frontend build (see report). What this
probe DOES prove is that the lex + parse layer:
  - produces a non-empty token stream,
  - terminates (the harness runs under a hard CPU cap; an infinite parse
    loop would be killed and the probe would never reach print_summary), and
  - produces a non-empty AST (the top-level SCRIPT node accrues children).

The probe exits with the number of failed assertions (0 == all passed).
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/powershell/powershell_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/powershell/powershell_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

@Reasoning:
Reads the cached child_count field (offset 24) of an AST node. The parser's
create_ast_node lays out nodes as type@0, parent@8, children@16,
child_count@24, data@32, capacity@48; add_child increments child_count, so
this is the authoritative count of accrued top-level statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "ast_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the node_type tag (offset 0) so the probe can confirm the root really
is the AST_SCRIPT node the parser is documented to return.
@End Reasoning
Process called "ast_node_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "PowerShell lex+parse smoke"

    Note:
    Representative PowerShell program exercising the full lexer/parser surface
    the brief enumerates:
    - comment-based help / # and <# #> comments
    - function with param() block, typed param [string]$Name, default value,
      and a [Parameter()] attribute
    - $variables, $script: and $env: scopes
    - cmdlet invocation (Verb-Noun) with named, positional and switch params
    - a multi-stage pipeline with $_
    - if / elseif / else
    - foreach, for, while, do-while
    - switch with -regex
    - try / catch / finally + throw
    - hashtable @{} and array @()
    - script block { }
    - "$($x)" string interpolation
    - comparison operators -eq / -ne / -gt / -match / -like
    :End Note
    Let source be "<#\nComment-based help block\n#>\nfunction Get-Greeting {\nparam(\n[Parameter(Mandatory=$true)]\n[string]$Name = \"World\",\n[int]$Count\n)\n$script:total = 0\n$env:PATH\nWrite-Output -InputObject $Name -NoNewline\nGet-ChildItem $env:HOME | Where-Object { $_.Length -gt 0 } | Sort-Object Name\nif ($Count -eq 0) {\n$result = @{ name = $Name; count = $Count }\n} elseif ($Count -gt 10) {\n$result = @(1, 2, 3)\n} else {\nthrow \"bad count\"\n}\nforeach ($item in $result) {\nWrite-Output \"$($item)\"\n}\nfor ($i = 0; $i -lt $Count; $i = $i + 1) {\n$total = $total + $i\n}\nwhile ($total -ne 0) {\n$total = $total - 1\n}\ndo {\n$total = $total + 1\n} while ($total -lt 5)\nswitch -regex ($Name) {\n\"^W\" { Write-Output \"starts with W\" }\ndefault { Write-Output \"other\" }\n}\ntry {\n$x = Get-Item -Path $Name\n} catch {\nWrite-Error $_\n} finally {\nWrite-Output \"done\"\n}\nif ($Name -match \"or\" -and $Name -like \"*ld\") {\nWrite-Output \"matched\"\n}\nreturn $result\n}\n# trailing comment\n"

    Let src_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "source is non-empty", src_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage A.1: tokenize ---
    Let lexer be proc tokenize from Lexer with source, src_len
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "lexer produced a token stream", lexer

    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "lexer produced tokens", token_count, 0

    Note: --- Stage A.2: parser construction ---
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser created", parser

    Let parser_token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "parser sees the lexer token count", parser_token_count, token_count

    Note: --- Stage A.3: parse (must terminate under the CPU cap) ---
    Let script be proc parse_script from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser produced an AST", script

    Let root_type be proc ast_node_type with script
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "AST root is AST_SCRIPT", root_type, 1

    Let child_count be proc ast_child_count with script
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "AST root has top-level statements", child_count, 0

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
